    en: "Every NY rental — residential or commercial — comes with an automatic right for the tenant to use and enjoy the property without serious interference by the landlord. NY courts call this the implied covenant of quiet enjoyment. The right applies whether or not the lease mentions it. Substantial interference by the landlord — repeated unauthorized entry, shutoff of essential services, ongoing construction noise, harassment to force the tenant out — gives the tenant a right to damages, rent abatement, or in serious cases the right to leave the lease early (called constructive eviction). The right is separate from the warranty of habitability under RPL 235-b, which covers basic livability."
